                    <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bib1489-1">BHO, 1082-85 ; AMS, VI, 32-52.
Lewis, Holy Women, 218- 44 (syr.) ; 168- 84 (trad.).
Sur le culte de Sophie au Liban, notamment invoquee contre Ia malaria, cf. Fiey,
"Saints", 38-39.
M. van Esbroeck, "Le saint comme symbole", dans S. Hackel, ed., The Byzantine
Saint (London, 1981), 128-40.
BS, XI, 1277-80 (A. Amore/M. Chiara Celletti).</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note type="abstract">Sophie or "wisdom" with her three daughters, Faith, Hope, and Charity, were martyred in Rome under Hadrian. Sophie was invoked as a saint to fight malaria.</note>
                    <note type="disambiguation">with pistis, elpis, agape</note>
                    <event type="attestation" xml:id="attestation1489-1" source="#bib1489-1">
                        <p xml:lang="en">Sopiya is commemorated in <title ref="http://syriaca.org/work/370">Sophia and her Daughters Pistis, Elpis and Agape (text)</title>.</p>
                    </event>
                    <event type="attestation" xml:id="attestation1489-2" source="#bib1489-1">
